Under-5 Mortality: A Global Perspective

Author

Padmaja Huprikar(A00010704)

Introduction

Child mortality remains one of the most pressing global challenges. This report explores trends and disparities in under-5 mortality across countries, continents, and genders using UNICEF data. Visualizations are created using Python with Polars and Plotnine.

Chart 1: Global Average Mortality Trend Over Time

This chart tracks the global average under-5 mortality rate across years, highlighting an overall declining trend and reflecting progress in healthcare access and maternal support.

Code 
import polars as pl
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, labs, theme_minimal

# Load and prepare data in Polars
df = pl.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")
df = df.rename({col: col.strip() for col in df.columns})
df = df.filter(pl.col("indicator").str.to_lowercase().str.contains("mortality"))
df = df.drop_nulls(subset=["obs_value", "time_period", "country"])

# Group by year and calculate average mortality
avg_df = df.group_by("time_period").agg(
    pl.col("obs_value").mean().alias("avg_mortality")
).sort("time_period")

# Convert to pandas for plotnine
avg_df_pd = avg_df.to_pandas()
avg_df_pd["time_period"] = avg_df_pd["time_period"].astype(int)

# Plot with regression line
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, labs, theme_minimal

plot = (
    ggplot(avg_df_pd, aes(x="time_period", y="avg_mortality"))
    + geom_point(color="#0072B2", size=3)
    + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=True, color="red")
    + labs(
        title="Trend of Average Under-5 Mortality Rate Over Time",
        x="Year",
        y="Average Under-5 Mortality Rate"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
)

plot

# Use most recent year (2022) if available

    df_pd[df_pd["time_period"] == latest_year]
    .sort_values("obs_value", ascending=False)
    .head(15)

# Bar chart

This scatter plot shows per-country mortality across time, color-coded by continent. Regression lines capture overall trends, showing steady improvement globally though some continents lag behind.

Code 
import polars as pl
import pandas as pd
import pycountry
import pycountry_convert as pc
from plotnine import *

# Load data
df = pl.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")
df = df.rename({col: col.strip() for col in df.columns})
df = df.filter(pl.col("indicator").str.to_lowercase().str.contains("mortality"))
df = df.drop_nulls(subset=["obs_value", "time_period", "country"])

# === Map country to continent ===
def get_continent(country_name):
    try:
        country = pycountry.countries.get(name=country_name)
        if not country:
            country = pycountry.countries.search_fuzzy(country_name)[0]
        alpha2 = country.alpha_2
        cont_code = pc.country_alpha2_to_continent_code(alpha2)
        return pc.convert_continent_code_to_continent_name(cont_code)
    except:
        return None

unique_countries = df.select("country").unique().to_series().to_list()
continent_df = pl.DataFrame({
    "country": unique_countries,
    "continent": [get_continent(c) for c in unique_countries]
}).drop_nulls()

# Join continent info
df_continent = df.join(continent_df, on="country", how="left").drop_nulls(subset=["continent"])

# Convert to pandas for plotnine
df_scatter = df_continent.to_pandas()
df_scatter["time_period"] = df_scatter["time_period"].astype(int)

# === Scatterplot with regression line per continent ===
scatter_continent = (
    ggplot(df_scatter, aes(x="time_period", y="obs_value", color="continent")) +
    geom_point(alpha=0.4, size=1.5) +
    geom_smooth(method="lm", se=False) +
    labs(
        title="Under-5 Mortality Rate Over Time by Continent",
        x="Year",
        y="Mortality Rate (per 1,000 live births)",
        color="Continent"
    ) +
    theme_minimal()
)

scatter_continent

# Step 1: Install required packages (if not already)
!pip install pycountry pycountry-convert plotnine polars

# Step 2: Import libraries
import polars as pl
import pycountry
import pycountry_convert as pc
from plotnine import *

# Step 3: Load the dataset (check the exact name you uploaded!)
df = pl.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")  #  correct file name

# Step 4: Clean and filter
df = df.rename({col: col.strip() for col in df.columns})
df = df.filter(pl.col("indicator").str.to_lowercase().str.contains("mortality"))
df = df.drop_nulls(subset=["obs_value", "time_period", "country"])

# Step 5: Map countries to continents
def get_continent(country_name):
    try:
        country = pycountry.countries.get(name=country_name)
        if not country:
            country = pycountry.countries.search_fuzzy(country_name)[0]
        alpha2 = country.alpha_2
        continent_code = pc.country_alpha2_to_continent_code(alpha2)
        return pc.convert_continent_code_to_continent_name(continent_code)
    except:
        return None

# Create continent map
unique_countries = df.select("country").unique().to_series().to_list()
continent_df = pl.DataFrame({
    "country": unique_countries,
    "continent": [get_continent(c) for c in unique_countries]
}).drop_nulls()

# Merge into main dataset
df_with_continent = df.join(continent_df, on="country", how="left").drop_nulls(subset=["continent"])

# Step 6: Aggregate mortality rates by continent and year
df_continent_trend = df_with_continent.group_by(["continent", "time_period"]).agg(
    pl.col("obs_value").mean().alias("avg_mortality")
).sort(["continent", "time_period"])

# Step 7: Convert to pandas for plotnine
df_continent_trend_pd = df_continent_trend.to_pandas()

# Step 8: Plot using plotnine
fig = (
    ggplot(df_continent_trend_pd, aes(x="time_period", y="avg_mortality", color="continent")) +
    geom_line(size=1.2) +
    geom_point(size=2) +
    labs(
        title="Under-5 Mortality Rate Over Time by Continent",
        x="Year",
        y="Avg Under-5 Mortality Rate (per 1,000 live births)",
        color="Continent"
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
        figure_size=(10, 6),
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, ha='right')
    )
)
